{"title_page": "Karla Aponte", "text_new": "{{short description|Puerto Rican model and beauty pageant titleholder}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name = Karla Aponte\n| photo =\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n<ref>{{Cite news\n| url            = https://futbolboricua.co/fpf-da-a-conocer-a-las-convocadas-de-u-20-para-la-segunda-fase-mundialista-en-haiti/\n| title          = FPF da a conocer a las convocadas de U 20 para la segunda fase mundialista en Hait\u00ed\n| website        = FutbolBoricua.net\n| first          = Edwin\n| last           = Jusino\n| language       = es\n| date           = 9 October 2015\n| accessdate     = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title = [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]]\n| nationalcompetition = [[Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017]]<br>(Top 12)<br>(Best Answer)<br>[[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Earth 2017]]<br>(Unplaced)<br>(Miss JACMI)<br>(Best in Eco-Video Presentation)<br>(Long Gown Competition)<br>(Swimsuit Competition)\n| birth_date= {{birth year and age|1998}}\n| birth_place = [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], Puerto Rico\n<!-- | residence (unknown parameter) = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]] -->\n| height = 1.73 m\n| eye_color = Green\n| hair_color = Blonde\n| skin_color = \n}}\n{{Spanish name|Aponte|Col\u00f3n}}\n'''Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n''' (born 1998) is a Puerto Rican [[Women's association football|footballer]], model and beauty pageant titleholder. She was crowned [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]] on August 9, 2017 at La Concha Renaissance Hotel in Condado, [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], she represented [[Puerto Rico]] at the [[Miss Earth 2017]] pageant.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAponte was born in [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico]]. She is a student of Business Administration at [[University of Puerto Rico]] in [[R\u00edo Piedras, Puerto Rico|R\u00edo Piedras]] Campus.\n\n==Pageantary==\n===Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017===\nAponte recently competed in [[Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017]] competition where she placed in the Top 10.\n\n===Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017===\nIn 2017, Aponte joined and won the [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]] pageant wherein she succeeded [[Franceska Toro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://missosology.org/miss-earth/43810-karla-victoria-aponte-miss-earth-puerto-rico-2017//|title=Karla Victoria Aponte is Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017|publisher=Missosology}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QEe0FxBGSDE|title=Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017 is Karla Victoria Aponte|date=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Earth 2017===\nAponte represented [[Puerto Rico]] in the [[Miss Earth 2017]] pageant in the [[Philippines]], she did not place among the finalists.\n\n==Football career==\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Karla Aponte\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n\n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1998}}\n| birth_place    = [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], Puerto Rico\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quepalo.com/karla-3274/|language=es|accessdate=12 April 2020|date=12 July 2016|title=De retar a la portera, a conquistar la pasarela|first=H\u00e9ctor|last=V\u00e1zquez Mu\u00f1iz|website=\u00a1Que Palo! Deportes}}</ref>\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| collegeyears1  = \n| college1       = \n| collegecaps1   = \n| collegegoals1  = \n| years1         = \n| clubs1         = \n| caps1          =  \n| goals1         = \n| nationalyears1 = 2015\n| nationalteam1  = {{Nwftu|20|Puerto Rico}}\n| nationalcaps1  = 1+\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate       = \n| ntupdate       = 21 June 2015\n}}\nAponte has represented Puerto Rico at the [[2015 CONCACAF Women's U-20 Championship qualification]], scoring once.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/karlavictoria.aponte Karla Victoria Aponte on Facebook Account]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/karlavictoriaaponteofficial/ Karla Victoria Aponte on Facebook Page]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/karlavaponte/ Karla Victoria Aponte on Instagram]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Franceska Toro]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth Puerto Rico]]\n|years=2017}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Krystal Xamairy]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Miss Earth 2017 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aponte, Karla}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Guaynabo, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Women's association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth 2017 contestants]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican female models]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Caribbean-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Puerto Rican model and beauty pageant titleholder}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name = Karla Aponte\n| photo =\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n<ref>{{Cite news\n| url            = https://futbolboricua.co/fpf-da-a-conocer-a-las-convocadas-de-u-20-para-la-segunda-fase-mundialista-en-haiti/\n| title          = FPF da a conocer a las convocadas de U 20 para la segunda fase mundialista en Hait\u00ed\n| website        = FutbolBoricua.net\n| first          = Edwin\n| last           = Jusino\n| language       = es\n| date           = 9 October 2015\n| accessdate     = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| title = [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]]\n| nationalcompetition = [[Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017]]<br>(Top 12)<br>(Best Answer)<br>[[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Earth 2017]]<br>(Unplaced)<br>(Miss JACMI)<br>(Best in Eco-Video Presentation)<br>(Long Gown Competition)<br>(Swimsuit Competition)\n| birth_date= {{birth year and age|1998}}\n| birth_place = [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], Puerto Rico\n<!-- | residence (unknown parameter) = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]] -->\n| height = 1.73 m\n| eye_color = Green\n| hair_color = Blonde\n| skin_color = \n}}\n{{Spanish name|Aponte|Col\u00f3n}}\n'''Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n''' (born 1998) is a Puerto Rican [[Women's association football|footballer]], model and beauty pageant titleholder. She was crowned [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]] on August 9, 2017 at La Concha Renaissance Hotel in Condado, [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], she represented [[Puerto Rico]] at the [[Miss Earth 2017]] pageant.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAponte was born in [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico]]. She is a student of Business Administration at [[University of Puerto Rico]] in [[R\u00edo Piedras, Puerto Rico|R\u00edo Piedras]] Campus.\n\n==Pageantary==\n===Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017===\nAponte recently competed in [[Miss Universe Puerto Rico 2017]] competition where she placed in the Top 10.\n\n===Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017===\nIn 2017, Aponte joined and won the [[Miss Earth Puerto Rico|Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017]] pageant wherein she succeeded [[Franceska Toro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://missosology.org/miss-earth/43810-karla-victoria-aponte-miss-earth-puerto-rico-2017//|title=Karla Victoria Aponte is Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017|publisher=Missosology}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QEe0FxBGSDE|title=Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017 is Karla Victoria Aponte|date=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Earth 2017===\nAponte represented [[Puerto Rico]] in the [[Miss Earth 2017]] pageant in the [[Philippines]], she did not place among the finalists.\n\n==Football career==\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Karla Aponte\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Karla Victoria Aponte Col\u00f3n\n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1998}}\n| birth_place    = [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], Puerto Rico\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quepalo.com/karla-3274/|language=es|accessdate=12 April 2020|date=12 July 2016|title=De retar a la portera, a conquistar la pasarela|first=H\u00e9ctor|last=V\u00e1zquez Mu\u00f1iz|website=\u00a1Que Palo! Deportes}}</ref>\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| collegeyears1  = \n| college1       = \n| collegecaps1   = \n| collegegoals1  = \n| years1         = \n| clubs1         = \n| caps1          =  \n| goals1         = \n| nationalyears1 = 2015\n| nationalteam1  = {{Nwftu|20|Puerto Rico}}\n| nationalcaps1  = 1+\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate       = \n| ntupdate       = 21 June 2015\n}}\nAponte has represented Puerto Rico at the [[2015 CONCACAF Women's U-20 Championship qualification]], scoring once.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/karlavictoria.aponte Karla Victoria Aponte on Facebook Account]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/karlavictoriaaponteofficial/ Karla Victoria Aponte on Facebook Page]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/karlavaponte/ Karla Victoria Aponte on Instagram]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Franceska Toro]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth Puerto Rico]]\n|years=2017}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Krystal Xamairy]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Miss Earth 2017 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aponte, Karla}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Guaynabo, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Women's association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth 2017 contestants]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican female models]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karla_Aponte"}
{"title_page": "You're No Good", "text_new": "{{short description|1963 single by Dee Dee Warwick}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      = You're_No_Good_-_Dee_Dee_Warwick.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dee Dee Warwick]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Don't Call Me\"\n| released   = [[1963 in music|1963]]\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| length     = 2:30\n| label      = [[Jubilee Records|Jubilee]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''You're No Good'''\" is a song written by [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]], first performed by [[Dee Dee Warwick]] for [[Jubilee Records]] in 1963 with production by [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]]. It has since been covered by many artists, including charting versions by [[Betty Everett]] in 1963, [[The Swinging Blue Jeans]] in 1964, and [[Linda Ronstadt]] in 1975, whose version was a number 1 hit in the United States.\n\n==Betty Everett version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Betty Everett]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Chained to Your Love\"\n| released   = [[1963 in music|1963]]\n| format     = 7\" single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| length     = 2:18\n| label      = [[Vee-Jay Records|Vee-Jay]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Prince of Players\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = [[The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\nThe song first became a hit in November 1963 when recorded by [[Betty Everett]] for [[Vee-Jay Records]] of [[Chicago]]. The single peaked at number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and at number 5 on \"Cashbox's R&B Locations\" chart.<ref name=\"Joel\">{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=193}}</ref>\n\nVee-Jay's head a&r man [[Calvin Carter]] found the song while visiting [[New York City]] in search of material for his label's roster and he originally intended to cut \"You're No Good\" with [[Dee Clark]] but, he recalled: \"when I went to rehearsal with the tune, it was so negative, I said, 'Hey, guys don't talk negative about girls, because girls are the record buyers. No, I better pass on that.' So I gave the song to Betty Everett.\" During the playback of Everett's track her label-mates [[the Dells]] \"were sitting on the wooden platform where the string players would sit... just stomping their feet on this wooden platform to the beat of the song as it was playing back... I told the engineer 'Let's do it again, and let's mic those foot sounds, 'cause it really gave it a hell of a beat.' So we did that, and boom, a hit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsnpubs.com/veejay/veejaystory3.html |title=The Vee-Jay Story, Page 3 |publisher=Bsnpubs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==The Swinging Blue Jeans version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Swinging Blue Jeans]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Don't You Worry About Me\"\n| released   = May 1964\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[beat music|Beat]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[His Master's Voice|HMV]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Walter J. Ridley]]\n| prev_title = [[Good Golly Miss Molly]]\n| prev_year  = 1964\n| next_title = Promise You'll Tell Her\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\nIn the UK [[the Swinging Blue Jeans]] had the hit version of \"You're No Good\" reaching number 3 in the summer of 1964. [[Sue Johnston]], then [[personal assistant|PA]] to [[Peter Brown (music industry)|Peter Brown]], was dating Swinging Blue Jeans drummer Norman Kuhlke and claims that she brought \"You're No Good\" to the attention of the Swinging Blue Jeans.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Sue\n| last=Johnston\n| year=201\n| title=Things I Couldn't Tell My Mother\n| edition=e-book\n| publisher=Random House\n| location= New York\n| isbn=9781409034698}}</ref> Their version also charted in [[France]] at number 26 and was successful enough regionally in the US to reach number 97 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Linda Ronstadt version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      = You're_No_Good_-_Linda_Ronstadt.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Linda Ronstadt]]\n| album      = [[Heart Like a Wheel]]\n| B-side     = \"[[I Can't Help It (If I'm Still in Love with You)]]\" (w/ [[Emmylou Harris]])\n| released   = November 19, [[1974 in music|1974]]\n| format     = 7\" single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=TMHr1g7T8gQC&pg=PT109&lpg=PT109&dq=linda+ronstadt+two+big+soft+rock+hits&source=bl&ots=0Ru9UztajK&sig=uEld0Qyfxc48XuMqO_b9rhO4V-Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwif_tLKoe_VAhXDTLwKHb_ABJ0Q6AEITTAL#v=onepage&q=linda+ronstadt+two+big+soft+rock+hits&f=false|title=The Secret History of Rock 'n' Roll|first=Christopher|last=Knowles|date=1 October 2010|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:44\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Peter Asher]]\n| prev_title = [[Love Has No Pride]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[When Will I Be Loved (song)|When Will I Be Loved]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n}}\n\n===Background===\n[[Linda Ronstadt]] began performing \"You're No Good\" to close her live shows in early 1973, after her band member [[Kenny Edwards]] suggested it to her. She first included it in her setlist while opening for [[Neil Young]]. Ronstadt gave an early televised performance of \"You're No Good\" on an episode of ''[[The Midnight Special (TV series)|The Midnight Special]]'' which was broadcast December 21, 1973.\n\nRonstadt recorded her album ''[[Heart Like a Wheel]]'' with producer [[Peter Asher]] in the summer of 1974 at [[the Sound Factory]]; \"You're No Good\" was a last-minute choice for recording, and while the song was Ronstadt's suggestion, Asher recalls: \"It was an odd coincidence. She\u2019d been doing the song already, and it was always a favorite song of mine...the version I fell in love with [being by] the Swinging Blue Jeans\".<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/classic-tracks/classic-track-you-re-no-good-linda-ronstadt/387624A| title=Classic Track: You're No Good| publisher=MixOnline.com| accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> The original backing track intended for Ronstadt's version of \"You're No Good\" was recorded July 1, 1974. According to Bob Warford, a guitarist in Ronstadt's touring band who played on the July 1 track, \"They were trying to do an R&B version of the song, which was actually closer to the way we did it live than to the released version. We played it at a faster tempo live, which we did on that recording [ie. of July 1].\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/> Ronstadt vetoed the July 1 arrangement; she recalls: \"It was just the wrong groove for me. I don\u2019t think I knew how to phrase around [the players], certainly no fault of theirs. They were fantastic.\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/>\n\nThe final recording of the Ronstadt version of \"You're No Good\" was made July 5, 1974. Ronstadt would recall: \"Ed Black, who played six-string guitar and pedal steel, started to play a rhythm riff on his [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]. Kenny Edwards...the bass player...echoed the riff in octaves. [[Andrew Gold]] added a sparse drum track, giving me a basic track to sing over. We did a few takes, picked one we liked, and then Andrew, who always played guitars and keyboards went to work with Peter [Asher]and began to work up layers of guitar, piano and percussion tracks.\" Ronstadt recalls that during a playback after several hours of work, [[Val Garay]], the engineer, accidentally erased Andrew Gold's guitar solo from the track, necessitating Asher and Gold's reconstructing that solo from scratch.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Linda\n| last=Ronstadt\n| year=2013\n| title=Simple Dreams: a musical memoir\n| edition=1st hardcover\n| publisher=Simon & Schuster\n| location= New York\n| pages=96\u201397\n| isbn=978-1-4516-6872-8}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 1974 a string arrangement - by [[Gregory Rose (musician)|Gregory Rose]] - was added to the track at [[Associated Independent Recording|AIR Studios]]. According to a ''Classic Tracks'' article by Mick Hurwitz at MixOnline.com: \"It ends with a strong, long held note, which Asher conceived, executed by Garay with a slow riding of the level on the string faders during the final mix.\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/>\n\n[[Capitol Records]] was unsure whether to release \"You're No Good\" or \"[[When Will I Be Loved (song)|When Will I Be Loved]]\" as the lead single off ''Heart Like a Wheel'', only deciding to release \"You're No Good\" a week after the album's release.\n\nLinda Ronstadt's version of \"You're No Good\" became the song's most successful cover. The track ascended to number 1 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart dated February 15, 1975. \"You're No Good\" was also an international hit for Ronstadt, reaching number 15 in Australia, number 17 in the Netherlands, and number 24 in New Zealand. The B-side of \"You're No Good\", \"I Can't Help It <small>(If I'm Still in Love with You)</small>, originally sung by [[Hank Williams]], also charted and was simultaneously a number 2 [[Hot Country Songs|C&W]] hit for Ronstadt. \"When Will I Be Loved\" was then issued as the follow-up single.<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', 15 November 1974, p.32</ref>\n\nBuoyed in part by the success of \"You're No Good\", the album ''[[Heart Like a Wheel]]'', which was released in late 1974, was a major success, and eventually went [[double platinum]]. It was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]].\n\nThe success of \"You're No Good\" set a precedent for Ronstadt's single releases which over the next five years would virtually all be remakes of classic rock and roll songs.\n\nIn a 1983 interview with the Los Angeles Times, Ronstadt expressed reservations about the recordings she had made during her 1970s heyday, specifically citing \"You're No Good\": \"I thought the production on 'You're No Good' was very good but [that] I didn't sing it very well. As a song it was just an afterthought. It's not the kind of song I got a lot of satisfaction out of singing.\"<ref>\"Ronstadt Marching to a Different Drum\", ''The Deseret News'', 14 December 1993 p. 4-SO</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1974\u201375)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canada]] Top Singles \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canada]] Adult Contemporary<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3925&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3925.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3925 |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dutch Top 40|Netherlands]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|24|artist=Linda Ronstadt|song=You're No Good|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Linda Ronstadt|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|10|artist=Linda Ronstadt|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n|US ''[[Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19750215.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426115818/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19750215.html |archivedate=2016-04-26 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia<ref>[http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ David Kent's ''Australian Chart Book 1970-1992''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |date=March 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|93\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.4057b&brws_s=1&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|website=www.collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1975.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1975/Top 100 Songs of 1975 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|50\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1975YESP.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021184320/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1975YESP.html |archivedate=2014-10-21 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other versions==\nArtists who have covered \"You're No Good\" include:\n*[[Phlegethon]]\n*[[Graham Bonney]]\n*[[Alma Cogan]] (unreleased)\n*[[Elvis Costello]]\n*[[Dusty Springfield]]\n*[[Ike & Tina Turner]]\n*[[Reba McEntire]]\n*[[The Muppets]]\n*[[Jose Feliciano]]\n*[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]\n*[[Aswad (band)|Aswad]]\n*[[Michael Bolton]] as Michael Bolotin\n*[[Ellie Campbell]]\n*[[Keith Hampshire]]\n*[[Jill Johnson]]\n*[[Rosie & The Originals]]\n*[[Little Milton]]\n*[[Anny Schilder]]\n*[[Floortje Smit]]\n*[[Van Halen]] (on ''[[Van Halen II]]'')\n*[[Wild Orchid (band)|Wild Orchid]]. \n* Los Rockets  (Mal Amor)\n*The 2004 album release ''[[California (Wilson Phillips album)|California]]'' by [[Wilson Phillips]] contains a version of \"You're No Good\" which like the Ronstadt version was produced by [[Peter Asher]] but radically reinvents the song. \n*International renderings include Finnish versions, \"Olet Paha\", a 1964 single release by [[:fi:Eddy and the Boys|Eddy and the Boys]], and \"Paha Oot\" on the 1975 album ''Bimbo'' by [[Marion Rung]]. \n*The [[Plastiscines]]' 2009 cover version from their album ''About Love'' was featured on season 6 episode 3 of [[True Blood]], \"You're No Good\".\n*[[Genya Ravan]] has indicated she vainly attempted to interest the producer of her 1974 album ''Goldie Zelkovitz'' in the idea of a remake of \"You're No Good\".\n*[[Maria Muldaur]], discussing in a 1985 interview how she \"didn't go out of [her] way to find followup hits\" to her 1973-74 breakthrough \"[[Midnight at the Oasis]]\", cited \"You're No Good\"  when explaining: \"I've turned down songs that have gone on to be hits for other people because I thought the lyrics were negative or neurotic\".<ref>''Sarasota Herald Tribune'' 21 October 1985 p.94</ref>\n\nAlso a French version:\n* Les Kelton - Au nom de la loi in 1964\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|linda-ronstadt|youre-no-good}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|7Cz__BzSJPY|Listen to \"You're No Good\"}} (Dee Dee Warwick)\n* {{YouTube|e47Ya2iVFRI|Listen to \"You're No Good\"}} (Linda Ronstadt)\n\n{{Linda Ronstadt}}\n\n[[Category:1963 singles]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1974 singles]]\n[[Category:Betty Everett songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:Linda Ronstadt songs]]\n[[Category:Jubilee Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Peter Asher]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Clint Ballard Jr.]]\n[[Category:Van Halen songs]]\n[[Category:Vee-Jay Records singles]]\n[[Category:His Master's Voice singles]]\n[[Category:Dee Dee Warwick songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1963 single by Dee Dee Warwick}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      = You're_No_Good_-_Dee_Dee_Warwick.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dee Dee Warwick]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Don't Call Me\"\n| released   = [[1963 in music|1963]]\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| length     = 2:30\n| label      = [[Jubilee Records|Jubilee]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''You're No Good'''\" is a song written by [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]], first performed by [[Dee Dee Warwick]] for [[Jubilee Records]] in 1963 with production by [[Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller]]. It has since been covered by many artists, including charting versions by [[Betty Everett]] in 1963, [[The Swinging Blue Jeans]] in 1964, and [[Linda Ronstadt]] in 1975, whose version was a number 1 hit in the United States.\n\n==Betty Everett version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Betty Everett]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Chained to Your Love\"\n| released   = [[1963 in music|1963]]\n| format     = 7\" single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| length     = 2:18\n| label      = [[Vee-Jay Records|Vee-Jay]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Prince of Players\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = [[The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\nThe song first became a hit in November 1963 when recorded by [[Betty Everett]] for [[Vee-Jay Records]] of [[Chicago]]. The single peaked at number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and at number 5 on \"Cashbox's R&B Locations\" chart.<ref name=\"Joel\">{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=193}}</ref>\n\nVee-Jay's head a&r man [[Calvin Carter]] found the song while visiting [[New York City]] in search of material for his label's roster and he originally intended to cut \"You're No Good\" with [[Dee Clark]] but, he recalled: \"when I went to rehearsal with the tune, it was so negative, I said, 'Hey, guys don't talk negative about girls, because girls are the record buyers. No, I better pass on that.' So I gave the song to Betty Everett.\" During the playback of Everett's track her label-mates [[the Dells]] \"were sitting on the wooden platform where the string players would sit... just stomping their feet on this wooden platform to the beat of the song as it was playing back... I told the engineer 'Let's do it again, and let's mic those foot sounds, 'cause it really gave it a hell of a beat.' So we did that, and boom, a hit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsnpubs.com/veejay/veejaystory3.html |title=The Vee-Jay Story, Page 3 |publisher=Bsnpubs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==The Swinging Blue Jeans version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Swinging Blue Jeans]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Don't You Worry About Me\"\n| released   = May 1964\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[beat music|Beat]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[His Master's Voice|HMV]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Walter J. Ridley]]\n| prev_title = [[Good Golly Miss Molly]]\n| prev_year  = 1964\n| next_title = Promise You'll Tell Her\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\nIn the UK [[the Swinging Blue Jeans]] had the hit version of \"You're No Good\" reaching number 3 in the summer of 1964. [[Sue Johnston]], then [[personal assistant|PA]] to [[Peter Brown (music industry)|Peter Brown]], was dating Swinging Blue Jeans drummer Norman Kuhlke and claims that she brought \"You're No Good\" to the attention of the Swinging Blue Jeans.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Sue\n| last=Johnston\n| year=201\n| title=Things I Couldn't Tell My Mother\n| edition=e-book\n| publisher=Random House\n| location= New York\n| isbn=9781409034698}}</ref> Their version also charted in [[France]] at number 26 and was successful enough regionally in the US to reach number 97 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Linda Ronstadt version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You're No Good\n| cover      = You're_No_Good_-_Linda_Ronstadt.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Linda Ronstadt]]\n| album      = [[Heart Like a Wheel]]\n| B-side     = \"[[I Can't Help It (If I'm Still in Love with You)]]\" (w/ [[Emmylou Harris]])\n| released   = November 19, [[1974 in music|1974]]\n| format     = 7\" single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=TMHr1g7T8gQC&pg=PT109&lpg=PT109&dq=linda+ronstadt+two+big+soft+rock+hits&source=bl&ots=0Ru9UztajK&sig=uEld0Qyfxc48XuMqO_b9rhO4V-Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwif_tLKoe_VAhXDTLwKHb_ABJ0Q6AEITTAL#v=onepage&q=linda+ronstadt+two+big+soft+rock+hits&f=false|title=The Secret History of Rock 'n' Roll|first=Christopher|last=Knowles|date=1 October 2010|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:44\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Clint Ballard, Jr.]]\n| producer   = [[Peter Asher]]\n| prev_title = [[Love Has No Pride]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[When Will I Be Loved (song)|When Will I Be Loved]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n}}\n\n===Background===\n[[Linda Ronstadt]] began performing \"You're No Good\" to close her live shows in early 1973, after her band member [[Kenny Edwards]] suggested it to her. She first included it in her setlist while opening for [[Neil Young]]. Ronstadt gave an early televised performance of \"You're No Good\" on an episode of ''[[The Midnight Special (TV series)|The Midnight Special]]'' which was broadcast December 21, 1973.\n\nRonstadt recorded her album ''[[Heart Like a Wheel]]'' with producer [[Peter Asher]] in the summer of 1974 at [[the Sound Factory]]; \"You're No Good\" was a last-minute choice for recording, and while the song was Ronstadt's suggestion, Asher recalls: \"It was an odd coincidence. She\u2019d been doing the song already, and it was always a favorite song of mine...the version I fell in love with [being by] the Swinging Blue Jeans\".<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/classic-tracks/classic-track-you-re-no-good-linda-ronstadt/387624A| title=Classic Track: You're No Good| publisher=MixOnline.com| accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> The original backing track intended for Ronstadt's version of \"You're No Good\" was recorded July 1, 1974. According to Bob Warford, a guitarist in Ronstadt's touring band who played on the July 1 track, \"They were trying to do an R&B version of the song, which was actually closer to the way we did it live than to the released version. We played it at a faster tempo live, which we did on that recording [ie. of July 1].\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/> Ronstadt vetoed the July 1 arrangement; she recalls: \"It was just the wrong groove for me. I don\u2019t think I knew how to phrase around [the players], certainly no fault of theirs. They were fantastic.\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/>\n\nThe final recording of the Ronstadt version of \"You're No Good\" was made July 5, 1974. Ronstadt would recall: \"Ed Black, who played six-string guitar and pedal steel, started to play a rhythm riff on his [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]. Kenny Edwards...the bass player...echoed the riff in octaves. [[Andrew Gold]] added a sparse drum track, giving me a basic track to sing over. We did a few takes, picked one we liked, and then Andrew, who always played guitars and keyboards went to work with Peter [Asher]and began to work up layers of guitar, piano and percussion tracks.\" Ronstadt recalls that during a playback after several hours of work, [[Val Garay]], the engineer, accidentally erased Andrew Gold's guitar solo from the track, necessitating Asher and Gold's reconstructing that solo from scratch.<ref>{{cite book\n| first=Linda\n| last=Ronstadt\n| year=2013\n| title=Simple Dreams: a musical memoir\n| edition=1st hardcover\n| publisher=Simon & Schuster\n| location= New York\n| pages=96\u201397\n| isbn=978-1-4516-6872-8}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 1974 a string arrangement - by [[Gregory Rose (musician)|Gregory Rose]] - was added to the track at [[Associated Independent Recording|AIR Studios]]. According to a ''Classic Tracks'' article by Mick Hurwitz at MixOnline.com: \"It ends with a strong, long held note, which Asher conceived, executed by Garay with a slow riding of the level on the string faders during the final mix.\"<ref name=\"Classic Tracks\"/>\n\n[[Capitol Records]] was unsure whether to release \"You're No Good\" or \"[[When Will I Be Loved (song)|When Will I Be Loved]]\" as the lead single off ''Heart Like a Wheel'', only deciding to release \"You're No Good\" a week after the album's release.\n\nLinda Ronstadt's version of \"You're No Good\" became the song's most successful cover. The track ascended to number 1 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart dated February 15, 1975. \"You're No Good\" was also an international hit for Ronstadt, reaching number 15 in Australia, number 17 in the Netherlands, and number 24 in New Zealand. The B-side of \"You're No Good\", \"I Can't Help It <small>(If I'm Still in Love with You)</small>, originally sung by [[Hank Williams]], also charted and was simultaneously a number 2 [[Hot Country Songs|C&W]] hit for Ronstadt. \"When Will I Be Loved\" was then issued as the follow-up single.<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', 15 November 1974, p.32</ref>\n\nBuoyed in part by the success of \"You're No Good\", the album ''[[Heart Like a Wheel]]'', which was released in late 1974, was a major success, and eventually went [[double platinum]]. It was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]].\n\nThe success of \"You're No Good\" set a precedent for Ronstadt's single releases which over the next five years would virtually all be remakes of classic rock and roll songs.\n\nIn a 1983 interview with the Los Angeles Times, Ronstadt expressed reservations about the recordings she had made during her 1970s heyday, specifically citing \"You're No Good\": \"I thought the production on 'You're No Good' was very good but [that] I didn't sing it very well. As a song it was just an afterthought. It's not the kind of song I got a lot of satisfaction out of singing.\"<ref>\"Ronstadt Marching to a Different Drum\", ''The Deseret News'', 14 December 1993 p. 4-SO</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1974\u201375)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australia]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canada]] Top Singles \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canada]] Adult Contemporary<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3925&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3925.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3925 |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dutch Top 40|Netherlands]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|24|artist=Linda Ronstadt|song=You're No Good|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Linda Ronstadt|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|10|artist=Linda Ronstadt|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}\n|-\n|US ''[[Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19750215.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426115818/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19750215.html |archivedate=2016-04-26 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia<ref>[http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ David Kent's ''Australian Chart Book 1970-1992''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |date=March 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|93\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.4057b&brws_s=1&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|website=www.collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1975.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1975/Top 100 Songs of 1975 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|50\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1975YESP.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021184320/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1975YESP.html |archivedate=2014-10-21 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other versions==\nArtists who have covered \"You're No Good\" include:\n*[[Phlegethon]]\n*[[Graham Bonney]]\n*[[Alma Cogan]] (unreleased)\n*[[Elvis Costello]]\n*[[Dusty Springfield]]\n*[[Ike & Tina Turner]]\n*[[Reba McEntire]]\n*[[The Muppets]]\n*[[Jose Feliciano]]\n*[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]\n*[[Aswad (band)|Aswad]]\n*[[Michael Bolton]] as Michael Bolotin\n*[[Ellie Campbell]]\n*[[Keith Hampshire]]\n*[[Jill Johnson]]\n*[[Rosie & The Originals]]\n*[[Little Milton]]\n*[[Anny Schilder]]\n*[[Floortje Smit]]\n*[[Van Halen]] (on ''[[Van Halen II]]'')\n*[[Wild Orchid (band)|Wild Orchid]]. \n* Los Rockets  (Mal Amor)\n*The 2004 album release ''[[California (Wilson Phillips album)|California]]'' by [[Wilson Phillips]] contains a version of \"You're No Good\" which like the Ronstadt version was produced by [[Peter Asher]] but radically reinvents the song. \n*International renderings include Finnish versions, \"Olet Paha\", a 1964 single release by [[:fi:Eddy and the Boys|Eddy and the Boys]], and \"Paha Oot\" on the 1975 album ''Bimbo'' by [[Marion Rung]]. \n*The [[Plastiscines]]' 2009 cover version from their album ''About Love'' was featured on season 6 episode 3 of [[True Blood]], \"You're No Good\".\n*[[Genya Ravan]] has indicated she vainly attempted to interest the producer of her 1974 album ''Goldie Zelkovitz'' in the idea of a remake of \"You're No Good\".\n*[[Maria Muldaur]], discussing in a 1985 interview how she \"didn't go out of [her] way to find followup hits\" to her 1973-74 breakthrough \"[[Midnight at the Oasis]]\", cited \"You're No Good\"  when explaining: \"I've turned down songs that have gone on to be hits for other people because I thought the lyrics were negative or neurotic\".<ref>''Sarasota Herald Tribune'' 21 October 1985 p.94</ref>\n\nAlso a french version:\n* Les Kelton - Au nom de la loi in 1964\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|linda-ronstadt|youre-no-good}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|7Cz__BzSJPY|Listen to \"You're No Good\"}} (Dee Dee Warwick)\n* {{YouTube|e47Ya2iVFRI|Listen to \"You're No Good\"}} (Linda Ronstadt)\n\n{{Linda Ronstadt}}\n\n[[Category:1963 singles]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1974 singles]]\n[[Category:Betty Everett songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:Linda Ronstadt songs]]\n[[Category:Jubilee Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Peter Asher]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Clint Ballard Jr.]]\n[[Category:Van Halen songs]]\n[[Category:Vee-Jay Records singles]]\n[[Category:His Master's Voice singles]]\n[[Category:Dee Dee Warwick songs]]\n", "name_user": "Rmhermen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther versions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You%27re_No_Good"}
